<GuideLayout title="UAE Labor Law Guide 2026: Employee Rights and Rules" description="Essential UAE labor law guide for 2026. Working hours, leave, termination, gratuity, WPS, and employee rights under Federal Decree-Law No. 33 of 2021." canonical="/uae/labor-law/" schemas={[buildBreadcrumbs(breadcrumbs), buildFAQSchema(faqs), buildArticleSchema("UAE Labor Law Guide 2026: Employee Rights and Rules", "Essential UAE labor law guide for 2026.", "https://gulfexpathub.com/uae/labor-law/", "2025-01-15", "2026-06-01")]} breadcrumbs={[{ name: "Home", url: "/" }, { name: "UAE", url: "/uae/guide/" }, { name: "Labor Law", url: "/uae/labor-law/" }]}>
<h1>UAE Labor Law Essentials 2026</h1>
<p>The UAE's labor framework is governed by Federal Decree-Law No. 33 of 2021, which replaced the previous 1980 labor law. This updated legislation modernized employment regulations, introduced new work models, strengthened employee protections, and aligned the UAE with international labor standards. Understanding these laws is essential for both employees and employers operating in the UAE.</p>
<h2>Employment Contracts</h2>
<p>Under the 2021 law, all employment contracts in the UAE are fixed-term (limited), with a maximum duration of 3 years that can be renewed. The previous distinction between limited and unlimited contracts has been eliminated for new contracts signed after February 2, 2022. Existing unlimited contracts were required to be converted by February 2023. Contracts must be in writing and registered with MoHRE. They must specify the job title, salary, benefits, duration, and other key terms. The employment contract, offer letter, and any amendments should be carefully reviewed before signing.</p>
<h2>Probation Period</h2>
<p>The probation period is a maximum of 6 months. During this period, either party can terminate with 14 days' written notice. If the employer terminates during probation, they must allow the employee to complete their notice period or pay in lieu. Employees who wish to leave during probation to join another UAE employer must serve 30 days' notice and the new employer must compensate the original employer for recruitment costs.</p>
<h2>Working Hours and Overtime</h2>
<p>Standard working hours are 8 hours per day or 48 hours per week. For Ramadan, hours are reduced by 2 hours daily. Overtime is compensated at 125% of the hourly rate for normal overtime and 150% for night hours (10 PM to 4 AM) or public holidays. Maximum overtime is 2 hours per day. Certain categories of workers (managerial, supervisory) may be exempt from overtime provisions.</p>
<h2>Leave Entitlements</h2>
<p>Annual leave is 30 calendar days per year after one year of service. During the first year, employees accrue 2 days per month. Sick leave is up to 90 days per year: 15 days full pay, 30 days half pay, 45 days unpaid. Maternity leave is 60 days (45 full pay, 15 half pay) with an additional 45 days unpaid if needed. Paternity leave is 5 working days within 6 months of birth. Bereavement leave is 5 days for spouse death and 3 days for other immediate family members. Hajj leave of 30 days (unpaid) is available once during employment.</p>
<h2>Termination and End of Service</h2>
<p>Either party can terminate the employment contract with written notice as specified in the contract (minimum 30 days, maximum 90 days). The employer must provide valid grounds for termination. End-of-service gratuity is calculated at 21 days' basic salary per year for the first 5 years and 30 days per year thereafter, capped at 2 years' total salary. See our <a href="/uae/gratuity-calculator/">UAE Gratuity Calculator</a> for exact calculations.</p>
<h2>Wage Protection System</h2>
<p>The WPS mandates electronic salary payments through approved channels. Employers who fail to pay within 15 days of the due date face escalating penalties. The system creates a transparent record that protects both employees and employers in dispute scenarios.</p>
